name.text: Reaction Forces and Free Body Diagram. Level 3.Question ID #1

questiontext.text:
A simply supported beam of length 114 cm is shown in the figure above. There are two supports, one at either end of the beam, hence reactions forces R1 and R2. There is a uniformly distributed load of mass 11 kg from 40 cm to 98 cm (measured from A).

By resolving forces and taking moments, determine the value of reaction forces, R1 and R2.

You may assume a value of g of 10 m/s2.

Give your answers to 2 d.p.

R1: {1:NUMERICAL:=43.42:0.4342#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N
R2: {1:NUMERICAL:=66.58:0.6658#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

generalfeedback.text:
For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where the uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The load value is the weight of the UDL (which is simply the product of the mass of the UDL and g).

The load position is the midpoint of the UDL.

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about A, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$ (1.14m x R2) - (0.69m x 110N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 66.58N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 110 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 43.42N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.

hint.text:
HINT

For a system to be in equilibirum, total forces in both x and y directions must be balanced.

Also, for a system to be in equilibrium, the sum of the clockwise moments must be equal to the sum of the anticlockwise moments.

For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, a uniformly distributed load (UDL) can be considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, when constructing an Equivalent Free Body Diagram.

By resolving forces and taking moments, determine the value of reaction forces, R1 and R2.

You may assume a value of g of 10 m/s2.

Give your answers to 2 d.p.

R1: {1:NUMERICAL:=13.08:0.1308#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N
R2: {1:NUMERICAL:=46.92:0.4692#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

generalfeedback.text:
For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where the uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The load value is the weight of the UDL (which is simply the product of the mass of the UDL and g).

The load position is the midpoint of the UDL.

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about A, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$ (1.17m x R2) - (0.915m x 60N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 46.92N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 60 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 13.08N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.

hint.text:
HINT

For a system to be in equilibirum, total forces in both x and y directions must be balanced.

Also, for a system to be in equilibrium, the sum of the clockwise moments must be equal to the sum of the anticlockwise moments.

For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, a uniformly distributed load (UDL) can be considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, when constructing an Equivalent Free Body Diagram.
